<subSubSection pageId="5" pageNumber="212" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="5.[151,1436,1211,1488]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">
After 
<emphasis box="[220,543,1247,1272]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">
<taxonomicName box="[220,364,1248,1272]" class="Secernentea" family="Aphelenchoididae" genus="Aphelenchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphelenchida" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" phylum="Nematoda" rank="species" species="fragariae">A. fragariae</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicName box="[378,543,1247,1272]" class="Secernentea" family="Aphelenchoididae" genus="Aphelenchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphelenchida" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" phylum="Nematoda" rank="species" species="ritzemabosi">A. ritzemabosi</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
has the highest number of reported hosts in both flowering plants and ferns (
<tableCitation box="[158,244,1283,1308]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,1217,1240]" captionTargetBox="[159,1268,1300,1900]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1: Number of associated plants reported for 13 plant-parasitic Aphelenchoides species on Pteridophyta, Pinophyta and Magnoliophyta. Complete database available at http: // nematodes. myspecies. info /" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF2D6669FFF7FFDEFF56FB7DE4F0FB7A" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" tableUuid="DF2D6669FFF7FFDEFF56FB7DE4F0FB7A">
Table 
<number box="[230,244,1284,1308]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[259,324,1283,1308]" captionStart="FIGURE 1" captionStartId="6.[151,250,1546,1568]" captionTargetBox="[165,1422,860,1504]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[154,1439,849,1509]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 1. Number of species / varieties of plants associated with foliar nematodes in ferns (Pteridophyta), monocots (Liliopsida), dicots (Magnoliopsida) and other botanical groups" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/242878/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">
Fig. 
<number box="[311,324,1284,1308]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="1.0">1</number>
</figureCitation>
). It is particularly problematic on 
<taxonomicName box="[715,899,1283,1308]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Chrysanthemum" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[715,899,1283,1308]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">Chrysanthemum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
L. and has previously been reported from circa 
<number box="[151,193,1320,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="200.0">200</number>
plant species (
<bibRefCitation author="Escuer" box="[364,610,1319,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" refString="Escuer, M. &amp; Bello, A. (2000) Nematodos del genero Aphelenchoides de interes fitopatologico y su distribucion en Espana. Boletin de sanidad vegetal. Plagas, 26, 47 - 63." type="journal article" year="2000">
Escuer &amp; Bello 
<number box="[551,610,1320,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="2000.0">2000</number>
</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="McCuiston" box="[623,817,1319,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" refString="McCuiston, J., Hudson L., Subbotin A., Davis E. &amp; Warfield, C. (2007) Conventional and PCR Detection of Aphelenchoides fragariae in diverse ornamental host plant species. Journal of Nematology, 39, 343 - 355." type="journal article" year="2007">
McCuiston 
<number box="[756,817,1320,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="2007.0">2007</number>
</bibRefCitation>
). That number increases to 
<quantity box="[1134,1207,1319,1344]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.1534" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" unit="in" value="321.0">321 in</quantity>
this paper with 
<number box="[1394,1436,1320,1344]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="314.0">314</number>
flowering plants and seven ferns (
<tableCitation box="[541,627,1355,1380]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,1217,1240]" captionTargetBox="[159,1268,1300,1900]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="TABLE 1: Number of associated plants reported for 13 plant-parasitic Aphelenchoides species on Pteridophyta, Pinophyta and Magnoliophyta. Complete database available at http: // nematodes. myspecies. info /" httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF2D6669FFF7FFDEFF56FB7DE4F0FB7A" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" tableUuid="DF2D6669FFF7FFDEFF56FB7DE4F0FB7A">
Table 
<number box="[614,627,1356,1380]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="1.0">1</number>
</tableCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Escuer" box="[654,916,1355,1380]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" refString="Escuer, M. &amp; Bello, A. (2000) Nematodos del genero Aphelenchoides de interes fitopatologico y su distribucion en Espana. Boletin de sanidad vegetal. Plagas, 26, 47 - 63." type="journal article" year="2000">
Escuer &amp; Bello (
<number box="[849,908,1356,1380]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="2000.0">2000</number>
)
</bibRefCitation>
mentioned that several weed species or noncultivated plants are suitable hosts for this species and further studies should be addressed to confirm this possibility. Reports in 
<taxonomicName authority="Bercht. &amp; J. Pres" authorityName="Bercht. &amp; J. Pres" box="[407,734,1427,1452]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Asteraceae Bercht. &amp; J. Pres</taxonomicName>
are especially numerous (see online database) and around 
<number box="[1408,1436,1427,1452]" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" value="85.0">85</number>
species of this family have been mentioned as associated plants with 
<taxonomicName box="[924,1087,1463,1488]" class="Secernentea" family="Aphelenchoididae" genus="Aphelenchoides" kingdom="Animalia" order="Aphelenchida" pageId="5" pageNumber="212" phylum="Nematoda" rank="species" species="ritzemabosi">
<emphasis box="[924,1087,1463,1488]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="212">A. ritzemabosi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
